| Notes                   = 
* In July 2004, {{WP|Bryan Singer}}, the director of the first two ''X-Men'' films, left the project during early pre-production, in order to direct the film ''{{WP|Superman Returns}}''.  He was joined by ''X2'' screenwriters [[Dan Harris]]  and [[Michael Dougherty]],  composer/editor John Ottman, and cast member {{WP|James Marsden}}.  Among the choices for replacements were {{WP|Darren Aronofsky}}, [[Joss Whedon]], {{WP|Rob Bowman (filmmaker)|Rob Bowman}}, {{WP|Alex Proyas}}, and {{WP|Zack Snyder}}.

* In March 2005, Matthew Vaughn was hired as the new director for the project. He cast {{WP|Kelsey Grammer}}  as [[Henry McCoy (Earth-10005)|Beast / Dr. Henry "Hank" McCoy]], {{WP|Dania Ramirez}} as [[Callisto (Earth-10005)|Callisto]] and {{WP|Vinnie Jones}}  as [[Cain Marko (Earth-10005)|Juggernaut / Cain Marko]], but family issues reportedly led him to withdraw before shooting began.  Vaughn was replaced by Singer's friend {{WP|Brett Ratner}},<ref name="USATODAY">{{cite web | title=Franchise's fans reverse stand on new director | publisher=USA Today | work=usatoday.com | url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2006-05-24-xmen-ratner_x.htm | accessdate=5 June 2006 | date=May 24, 2005 | author=Scott Bowles}}</ref> who was among those originally considered to direct the first film &mdash; and coincidentally was considered by Warner Brothers to direct the 2006 ''Superman'' project before it evolved into ''Superman Returns''.

* The film was originally scheduled for a May 5, 2006 release, but was pushed back to May 26 of the same year due to production delays.

* The film began filming in August 2005 and ended in January 2006.

| Trivia                  = 
* Many of the cast members from the previous two X-Men films returned, the major exceptions being {{WP|Alan Cumming}}, who portrayed [[Kurt Wagner (Earth-10005)|Nightcrawler / Kurt Wagner]] and {{WP|Kelly Hu}}, who portrayed [[Yuriko Oyama (Earth-10005)|Deathstrike / Yuriko Oyama]], from {{sl|X2 (film)}}. Both of whom signed two-film contracts. However, Hu's character was killed by Wolverine in the previous film and Alan Cumming was reportedly uncomfortable with the long hours he had to take with the Nightcrawler makeup. The part for Nightcrawler was so minimal in the third film that he felt it was not worth it to go through the long and costly makeup process when he was barely in the film, and the character was cut.<ref name="Screen Rant">{{Cite web | title=X-Men 3: Why Nightcrawler Didn't Return For The Last Stand | publisher=Screen Rant | work=screenrant.com | url=https://screenrant.com/xmen-last-stand-nightcrawler-return-makeup-cummings/ | accessdate=14 March 2023 | date=November 21, 2020 | author=Kristen Abernathy}}</ref> He did agree, however, to do voice work for the character for the video game based on the film. {{WP|James Marsden}} did appear in the film as [[Scott Summers (Earth-10005)|Cyclops / Scott Summers]], despite reported scheduling conflicts with ''Superman Returns''.

* {{WP|Halle Berry}} stated during interviews for ''X2'' that she would not return as [[Ororo Munroe  (Earth-10005)|Storm]] in the third film unless the character had a significant presence comparable to the comic-book version.  Brett Ratner also felt Storm required a larger role and there was little difficulty reaching an agreement.<ref name="UGO 2">{{Cite web|title=Halle Berry of X-Men: The Last Stand | publisher=UGO | work=ugo.com | url=http://www.ugo.com/summermovies/Content/ProductViewer.aspx?BlogsPageNumber=3&ProductID=172 | accessdate=6 June 2006 | date=May 24, 2006 | author=Daniel Robert Epstein}}</ref>

* Filmmakers considered using the Beast character since the first X-Men movie, but budget constraints ruled him out; however, {{MM|Steve Bacic}}  is identified as Hank McCoy when he appears on a television screen in a cameo role in ''X2''. 

* The events of this movie occur in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.25moments.com|title=X-Men: 25 Moments|accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref>

{{Navigation
| title = Comparison with the comics
| body  = ''X-Men: The Last Stand'' draws much of its plot and characters from the source comic books; however, while some of the X-Men characters and details remain similar, a number of comic book elements are altered for the adaptation.

The film's plot concerning the emergence of the Phoenix draws from Chris Claremont's 1980 "Dark Phoenix Saga" in ''The Uncanny X-Men''.  Whereas in the film, the Phoenix is Jean Grey's evil "split personality", in the comics, the [[Phoenix Force|Phoenix]] is a fiery, Phoenix-like alien entity and force of nature that bonds with Jean.  The cure for mutant powers can be seen in Joss Whedon's 2004 "Gifted" story arc in ''Astonishing X-Men''.

''X-Men: The Last Stand'' is the first, and so far only, X-Men film to feature the five original X-Men -- Cyclops, Iceman, Beast, Angel, and Jean Grey on the team; however, the characters' backstories and positions within the team are altered. Other characters are translated even more loosely. Many of the Brotherhood shown in the film, for instance, including [[Spike]], Psylocke and Multiple Man, are not Brotherhood villains in the comics. The mutant named Kid Omega resembles a character named [[Maxwell Jordan (Earth-616)|Quill]] in the comics, rather than the hyper-intelligent comic book [[Quintavius Quire (Earth-616)|Kid]]. In the film, [[Psylocke (Earth-10005)|Psylocke]] has a red dagger tattooed above her left eye, and she is able to hide in shadows; this is a reference to a period during which Psylocke was connected to a substance called the "[[Crimson Dawn]]", which gives her powers beyond her innate mutant abilities of [[telepathy]] and [[telekinesis]] that manifests as a psionic knife/[[katana (Earth-616)|katana]]. Brotherhood member Callisto is depicted with superhuman speed and the ability to sense mutants' power levels. In the comics, Callisto is the leader of the [[Morlocks]] and has neither ability, instead, possessing acute senses.  In the comics, Juggernaut is Xavier's human step-brother who acquires power when he finds a mystical stone; in ''X-Men: The Last Stand'', however, Juggernaut is a mutant, and there is no mention of a relationship with the professor. Whereas he is usually gruff and violent in the comics, his line "Don't you know who I am? I'm the Juggernaut, bitch!" alludes not to the comics, but to a video (''The Juggernaut Bitch!!'') in which the video's creators talk over footage from {{sl|X-Men: The Animated Series}}.

Familiar details from the X-Men mythos permeate the film. The X-Men are shown training in the trademark [[Danger Room]], a training complex within the [[Xavier's School for Gifted Youngsters|X-Mansion]]. A giant, mutant-hunting [[Sentinels|Sentinel]] robot appears as a hologram inside the Danger Room. The [[Glossary:Fastball Special|fastball special]], in which Colossus throws Wolverine toward an opponent, appears in the film twice, the targets being Magneto and a Sentinel. Beast's line "Oh my stars and garters!" appears frequently in the comics. One of the president's advisers is named Trask, an allusion to [[Bolivar Trask (Earth-616)|Bolivar Trask]], creator of the Sentinels. Kitty Pryde's run through the pharmaceutical complex while being chased by the Juggernaut mirrors the character's similar fight against an alien in {{cl|Uncanny X-Men Vol 1 143}}. Finally, Wolverine's killing Jean bears some similarity when he killed his love [[Mariko Yashida (Earth-616)|Mariko Yashida]] at her request to spare her a painful death from poison (see {{cl|Wolverine Vol 2 57}}), as well as in ''New X-Men'', in which he kills Jean to spare her from a more agonizing death burning up in the Sun.}} 

==Adaptations==
===Novelization===
The novelization of the film, written by comic book writer Chris Claremont, was released on May 16, 2006.<ref>{{cite book | isbn=0345492110 | title=[[X-Men: The Last Stand#Novelization|X-Men: The Last Stand]] | publisher=Del Rey | last=Claremont | first=Chris | authorlink=Chris Claremont}}</ref>  The novelization of the movie differs significantly from the film. 

{{Navigation
| title = Difference between Movie and Novelization
| body  = In the novel, young Jean Grey discovers her powers after an accident that takes her best friend's life. Angel officially joins the X-Men and travels with them to Alcatraz Island instead of going on his own. Storm spares Callisto's life, which is more in line with Professor Xavier's views on violence. Rogue decides to keep her powers in the end, and Beast stays at the school as a teacher. Iceman takes an unconscious Pyro away from Alcatraz. The attack on Alcatraz is referred to as M-Day, a reference to the "[[Decimation |Decimation of mutantkind]]" storyline in the comic books. Moira MacTaggert visits Magneto in the park, presumably offering an antidote to the cure, which he refuses because as the book says: "He couldn't go back. That path had brought nothing but grief, to those he cared for, those who trusted him, to himself. This was better." This suggests that in the novel Magneto turns over a new leaf before discovering a slight return of his powers. Unlike the film, the novel does not allude to Xavier's resurrection.}} 
